						<summary>

						<p>Pillar in the Dantēśvarī temple.</p>						

						<p><hi rend="bold">Jagadēkabhūshaṇa-mahārāja Narasiṁhadēva Śaka 1147: 1224 A.D.</hi></p>						

						<p>This damaged inscribed pillar was then being used as a <hi rend="italic">yūpa</hi> (i.e., sacrificial post). This slab is inscribed on all the four faces and at the top. It contains fifty lines of writing and a major portion is damaged. </p>						

						<p>The extant portion is in Telugu characters of 13th century. The details of date given are Śaka 1147, Jyēshṭha ba 10. The date corresponds to 13th June 1224 A.D. But if the year 1147 is taken as an expired one, then it would correspond to 2nd June 1225 A.D.</p>						

						<p>It seems to record some gift to the temple of Dēvī on the above date. It is not clear as to the donor of the grant.</p>						

						<p>(Published in <hi rend="italic">Epigraphia Indica,</hi> Vol. X, pp. 40-42 and <hi rend="italic">South Indian Inscriptions,</hi> Vol. X, No. 648).</p>						

						</summary>
